The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 At least seven people were injured in a traffic pile-up on CR Avenue, near Sovabazar Metro station, around 11.45 am on Tuesday.

 he accident occurred when the driver of an Ariadaha-Bagbazar minibus lost control and hit the minibus in front. The second vehicle lunged forward to collide with a Calcutta Tramways Company (CTC) bus plying on the Airport-Esplanade route. The CTC bus in turn hit a taxi.

 f the seven injured, four were in the taxi. They were taken to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital. The vehicles have been impounded by Shyampukur police station. A case of negligent and rash driving has been lodged against the driver of the first minibus, who is absconding.

 A fire broke out in a tannery at Tiljala late on Monday. Firemen said drums of chemicals stored in the tannery, caught fire following a short circuit. Three tenders brought the blaze under control in an hour. No one was injured.

 n another accident, three people were injured in a fire in a shanty on Dilkhusha Road in the Park Circus area late on Monday. They were discharged after treatment.

 Balaram Sharma, 24, died of burns on Tuesday morning. He had set himself on fire at his Kashaibagan Lane residence on Monday night, in front of his sister-in-law Shakuntala Sharma and her son. The mother and the son, too, suffered burns.

 Tanmay Mullick, 57, was killed on Monday night after the cycle he was riding was hit by a lorry on Budge Budge Trunk Road. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where he succumbed to injuries.

 An 18-year-old housewife died under mysterious circumstances in Barrackpore, on the northern fringes of the city, on Tuesday. The body of Rupa Roy was found hanging from the ceiling of her room. Her husband and brother-in-law are absconding. Some others from her husband?s family have been arrested. The death is being investigated. 

 The body of an unidentified youth was found on the Patipukur railway overbridge on Tuesday morning. Police said the body bore no signs of injury. It is not clear whether or not the youth committed suicide.

 A lecture on ?Rabindranath Tagore and Blindness? was organised at the central hospital of South Eastern Railway, at Garden Reach, on Monday evening. Ophthalmologist Anil Kumar Mondal delivered the lecture. P.K. Chatterjee, Nirban Gangopdhyay and other ophthalmologists were present on the occasion.

 Noor Khan Biswas, 45, who was hit by an auto-rickshaw in Howrah town on Monday evening, succumbed to his injuries at Howrah District Hospital on Tuesday. The driver is absconding.

 Four people were arrested at Medical College and Hospital on Monday night for staying on the compound illegally.

